"Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Donal, Cian, Cormac, Fergus, Finbarr, James Patrick, Jarlath, John Patrick, Sinead, Siobhan.","Irish (Dublin and Galway): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Cearbhaill</b> ‘descendant of <i>Cearbhall</i>’ (see   Carroll  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Carroll","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of <b>Ó Cearbhaill</b> or <b>Mac Cearbhaill</b> ‘descendant (or son) of <i>Cearbhall</i>’, a personal name perhaps based on <i>cearbh</i> ‘hacking’ and hence originally a byname for a butcher or a fierce warrior.","English and Scottish: variant of   Carrell  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. William O'Carroll was born in 1295, in County Galway, Ireland. She had at least 3 sons and 1 daughter with William O'Carroll."},"et":{"1295–":"1295–Surnud","1290–Male":"1290–Surnud","1320–Female":"1320–Surnud","1321–1380":"1321–1380","1325–1410":"1325–1410","1325–Male":"1325–Surnud","1295–Female":"1295–Surnud","1325":"1325","1410":"1410","1321":"1321","1320":"1320","1295":"1295","about 1320":"umbes 1320","1380":"1380","1290":"1290","County Galway, Ireland":"County Galway, Iirimaa","Ireland":"Iirimaa"},"fi":{"1295–":"1295–Kuollut","1290–Male":"1290–Kuollut","1320–Female":"1320–Kuollut","132